Legal Fellow

The mission of The Advocates for Human Rights is to implement international human rights standards to promote civil society and reinforce the rule of law. By involving volunteers in research, education, and advocacy, we build broad constituencies in the United States and select global communities.

The Advocates for Human Rights was founded in 1983 by a group of Minnesota attorneys who recognized Minnesota’s unique spirit of social justice as an opportunity to promote and protect human rights worldwide. 

Today, The Advocates continues to broaden the impact of its work in Minnesota and around the world.
History of WATCH and Court Monitoring

WATCH was originally founded in 1992 in Minneapolis, Minnesota by Susan Lenfestey.

WATCH first began by monitoring court solely in Hennepin  County. Monitoring began in Ramsey County in 2014 and Washington County in 2017. 

WATCH has worked to make the justice system more responsive to crimes of violence, focusing on greater safety for victims of violence and greater accountability for violent offenders.

On June 20, 2019, WATCH officially became a project of The Advocates for Human Rights and continues to monitor court in all three counties.

Although more often used in formal testing situations MCQs can be used as a testing tool to stimulate thought and discussion on topics students may feel a little reticent in responding to. When designing a MCQ test consider the following:
  • What learning outcomes are the questions testing
  • What intellectual skills are being tested
  • What are the language skills of the audience
  • Gender and cultural issues
  • Avoid grammar language and question structures that might provide clues
Enter the question stem. The quest should be clear and unambiguous. Avoid negative premises as these can tend to be ambiguous.

When building an MCQ consider the following:
  • Use phrases that learners are familiar with and have encountered in their study
  • Keep responses concise
  • There should be some consistency between the stem and the responses
  • Provide enough options to challenge learners to think about their response
  • Try to make sure that correct responses are not more detailed than the distractors
  • Distractors should be incorrect but plausible

Introduction to Domestic Violence, Sexual Assault and Child Abuse

• Criminal Sexual Conduct

- 1st degree, 2nd degree, 3rd degree

  • Domestic Abuse

- Domestic Abuse, Domestic Assault by Strangulation, Terroristic Threats, Assault in the 1st, 2nd, 3rd and 5th degree, Burglary in the 1st degree. 

  • Child Abuse and Endangerment

- Child Endangerment,  Mal Punishment of a Child and Possession of Pornography 

  • Civil Orders for Protection

- Violation of Order for Protection and Order for Protection Civil Hearings 

  • Sex Trafficking  

- Promote, Solicit and Engage in Prostitution and Human Trafficking

A pattern of abusive and threatening behaviors that may include physical, emotional, economic and sexual violence as well as intimidation, isolation and coercion. The purpose of domestic violence is to establish and exert power and control over another; men most often use it against their intimate partners, such as current or former spouses, girlfriends, or dating partners.

- The Advocates for Human Rights

Statute 518B

Domestic abuse occurs to a family or household member if committed by a family or household member. Household members are defined as: 

Spouse, former spouse, parents and children, person related by blood, currently living together or have lived together in the past, have a child in common, or are in a significant or sexual relationship.

Statute 609.2247

“Strangulation” means intentionally impeding normal breathing or circulation of the blood by applying pressure to the throat or neck or by blocking the nose or mouth of another person.

“A nonconsensual sexual contact that is obtained through coercion or the use or threat of force. Sexual assault is not a manifestation of uncontrolled desire, attraction, or arousal; it  is a deliberate act of gender-based violence and an expression of power, control and domination over another.”

- The Advocates for Human Rights

Statutes 609.221 to 609.224

  • 1st degree – “great bodily harm”; or assault with deadly force against police officer
  • 2nd degree – “substantial bodily harm” and uses a dangerous weapon
  • 3rd degree – “substantial bodily harm”; or pattern of child abuse; or assaults a child under 4 years old and inflicts bodily harm
  • 4th degree – assault against a police officer, firefighter, emergency medical personnel, certain government/public/school employees; or assault motivated by race, gender, sexual orientation, or other bias. This charge is never “ours” meaning we do not monitor this case in court.
  • 5th degree – misdemeanor: an act committed with intent to cause fear of bodily harm or death; or intentionally inflicts or attempts to inflict bodily harm upon another.

609.321 PROSTITUTION AND SEX TRAFFICKING; DEFINITIONS.

Subd. 7a.Sex trafficking.

"Sex trafficking" means:

(1) receiving, recruiting, enticing, harboring, providing, or obtaining by any means an individual to aid in the prostitution of the individual; or

(2) receiving profit or anything of value, knowing or having reason to know it is derived from an act described in clause (1).

Subd. 7b.Sex trafficking victim.

"Sex trafficking victim" means a person subjected to the practices in subdivision 7a.

Subd. 8.Prostitute.

"Prostitute" means an individual who engages in prostitution by being hired, offering to be hired, or agreeing to be hired by another individual to engage in sexual penetration or sexual contact.

Subd. 9.Prostitution.

"Prostitution" means hiring, offering to hire, or agreeing to hire another individual to engage in sexual penetration or sexual contact, or being hired, offering to be hired, or agreeing to be hired by another individual to engage in sexual penetration or sexual contact.


You can find the entire MN Statute here: Sex Trafficking Statutes in MN

Statutes 609.342 to 609.3451

  • 1st degree - requires penetration or contact with a child under 13 years and one of the following: armed with a weapon; exhibits force or coercion; offender knows victim is mentally impaired or incapacitated
  • 2nd degree - same as 1st degree except no penetration, only contact.
  • 3rd degree - requires penetration and has less of an age disparity than 1st degree. This degree includes sexual abuses by clergy, psychotherapist, etc.
  • 4th degree - same as 3rd degree except no penetration, only contact.
  • 5th degree - gross misdemeanor. Offender engages in nonconsensual sexual conduct contact (e.g. touching), or offender engages in public masturbation or lewd exhibition of genitals in front of minor under age 16.

• In 2009 the Twin Cities was identified by the FBI as the second largest area for child prostitution in the Nation.
  • In 2009 the Minnesota laws on prostitution were amended to explicitly make sex trafficking a crime.
  • In 2011 Minnesota passed the Safe Harbor Laws.  
    • Part 1 of the law went into effect in 2011 and added the definition of sexually exploited youth in Minnesota’s child protection codes.
    • Part 2 of the law went into effect August 1st, 2014, mandating that anyone under the age of 18 who is a victim of sex trafficking cannot be treated as a criminal or be labeled as a “delinquent child.”

  • The Advocates became a leader in Minnesota’s anti-trafficking efforts. In 2011, The Advocates led the effort to enact Minnesota’s Safe Harbor for Sexually Exploited Youth Act. 

  • In late 2013, WATCH began prioritizing cases of sex trafficking as they moved slowly through the Hennepin County criminal justice system.  In 2013, WATCH committed to monitor all cases of sex trafficking in Hennepin County from start to finish.

Statute 609.377

A parent, legal guardian, or caretaker who, by an intentional act or a series of intentional acts with respect to a child, evidences unreasonable force or cruel discipline that is excessive under the circumstances.

Crimes are divided into three categories based on the maximum possible length of imprisonment:

  • Misdemeanor; punishable by 90 days or less.
  • Gross Misdemeanor; punishable by one year or less.
  • Felony; punishable by imprisonment of more than 1 year up to life in prison.

Crimes can be brought to the attention of the authorities in a variety of ways.

  • Child reports abuse to a parent or loved one
  • Victim may contact police by calling 911
  • Routine welfare checks 
  • Investigations of separate or related offenses

Incident    ->   Report   ->    Investigation   ->    Arrest

Criminal activity is a crime against the state, not the individual. 

  • To say that a victim “brought charges” or “dropped a case” is incorrect.

Criminal cases are written:

State v. John Smith

1. The judge presides over the courtroom and ensures that the rules of court are followed on both sides.  The judge also decides on questions of evidence and the application of the rules of procedure.
  2. The prosecutor represents the state and the defense attorney represents the accused.  Their job is to work towards the best interest of whomever they represent.
  3. The court clerk is responsible for the administrative aspects of the trial. (administering oaths, taking charge of physical evidence)
  4. The bailiff or deputy is in charge of maintaining safety and security in the court and escorting the jury and in-custody defendants in and out of proceedings.
  5. The court reporter records everything that is said as part of the formal proceedings.
  6. Additionally, court interpreters may be present to assist with interpretation and translation services.

• Arrest   ->   First appearance
  • Someone is arrested then brought before a judge for a first appearance.

In a First Appearance hearing:

  • A public defender may be appointed. 
  • Defendant enters plea.
  • Judge sets bail & conditions (if any).

First appearance can be used as probable

cause hearing

  • The judge determines if there is enough evidence on behalf of the State to proceed.

In general, if a case is going to trial, a variety of court hearings will be held to prepare for it.

Appearances may include: 

  • Motion hearings
  • Change of venue hearings
  • Hearings to determine the admissibility of evidence
  • Jury selection (“voir dire”)

• An amount of money defendant must post to be released.
  • Returned to defendant when the case is concluded.
Ensures defendants shows up for next appearance.

• If defendant cannot afford bail, option to use a bail bonding service for assistance.
  • Defendant puts up a percentage of the bail, typically 10%
  • Bail bonding company guarantees the remaining amount to the court in the event the defendant doesn’t show up.

Judges can weigh certain factors when determining bail, including:

  • Risk of the defendant fleeing
  • Type of crime
  • Defendant’s danger to the community.

When ordering bail…

  • Judge may also set conditions of release.

examples: no contact with the victim    (DANCO), no drug/alcohol use, random UAs.

  • Defendants can also be released without bail, if the judge deems appropriate.

Conditional release OR release on own recognizance.

State has burden of proof.

  • The prosecutor must convince the jury or judge that the defendant is guilty beyond a reasonable doubt.

Unlike what you may see on television, most cases do not result in a trial.

Trials are expensive and time consuming, and there is often pressure for the parties to come to a settlement, known as a plea bargain, to resolve the case and avoid a trial.

Jury trial- traditionally composed of 12 individuals who determine the guilt or innocence of the defendant.


Judge or bench trial- where a judge hears the evidence and makes the determination.
These are what you will be observing in most cases. Please click on the sub-topics to learn more.

Plea OR conviction by jury sentencing

Pre-sentence investigation (PSI) 

will take place to help the judge determine the appropriate sentence. 

  • Completed by probation
  • Investigation of the defendant’s:
    • Prior criminal record
    • Family situation
    • Health 
    • Work history
    • Considers victim safety

• MN has sentencing guidelines that a judge must follow.
  • If the judge decided on a sentence outside the guidelines, it is called a departure (either upward or downward)

• MN allows victims to make a statement at sentencing or to submit a written statement about the impact the crime has had on them (or in the case of murder, the impact of the crime has on the surviving family members.) 
  • These can be very powerful experiences for victims and perhaps may be the first chance the victim has had to talk openly to the court about what happened.

• Prison/jail time
    • May be stayed; meaning the defendant won’t go directly to jail. If they violate probation, they will be arrested and sent to prison to serve their time.
  • Probation 
    • Each defendant put on probation is assigned a probation officer to report to.
  • Community service
  • Restitution
    • A payment made on behalf of the defendant to the state, victim or victim’s family.
  • Treatment 
    • Domestic abuse counseling, drugs or alcohol treatment, anger management, etc...

Commonly referred to as probation violation

  • A hearing is scheduled 
  • May result in new charges and/or having “stayed” time revoked.
  • If defendant denies violation, revocation (Morrissey) hearing is scheduled.

Courts most commonly learn about probation violations: 

  • From defendant’s probation officer
    • Violate condition of probation ordered at Sentencing
  • Arrested by authorities on another charge
    • Authorities may look up a defendant’s criminal history
  • Violated a No Contact Order or Order for Protection
    • Victim may call 911 to tell authorities defendant has tried to contact victim.

An order for protection (OFP) is a court order that tells an abuser to stop harming or threatening an individual.  They can also direct other behaviors, such as staying away from a victim, vacating the premises, and refraining from contacting the victim.
The Civil Order for Protection Process

• Orders for protection are a civil order that, if broken, have criminal sanctions. If the respondent violates the order, he or she would be subject to arrest and charged with a Felony .
  • OFPS were designed specifically to deal with the complicated dynamics of domestic violence.

  • Orders for protection can be effective tools for some victims but cannot guarantee safety.  It is up to each individual to determine if requesting an OFP would help or hurt the situation.
What to watch for, Monitoring Guidelines, and Paperwork
Which Courtrooms will you be observing?

• Hennepin County
    • Felony Arraignment Court (1st Appearances)
    • Domestic Violence Court 
    • Felony hearings at the Government Center
    • Order for Protection Court 
  • Ramsey County
    • Main Courthouse
  • Washington County
    • Main Courthouse

• Briefing and debriefing
    • Communicate with The Advocates prior to every shift to discuss cases and the calendar.
    • Please bring homework or reading material for any downtime in the courtroom.
  • Proper court attire & prohibited items
    • Anything but torn jeans, sweatpants, flip flops or shirts with provocative words.  You will be required to enter each courthouse through metal detectors. Please prepare for each shift with this in mind.
  • Cancellations 
    • Please call The Advocates 24 hours in advance, or if sick please, e-mail as soon as possible.

• You are a silent observer of the system.
  • Please do not discuss the cases you see, give feedback to any court personnel or discuss cases with anyone sitting in the gallery.
  • Monitors should not INITIATE conversation or feedback with judges.  On occasion the judge or other courtroom personnel may engage in conversation with you, which is welcomed.

• We do not observe testimonies of victims under the age of 13.
    • This is out of respect and to reduce the trauma for both victims and monitors.
  • When attending trials please enter and exit quietly. 
  • If you recognize a jury member, please leave the trial immediately.
  • Please be aware of who is around you in the halls, elevators and security lines etc.  Information relevant to the case may be said outside of the courtroom.
  • Deputies are only present in the courtroom if a defendant is in custody.
  • If you are ever worried about safety, notify the judicial clerk or leave the courtroom immediately.

We monitor the process and substance of court proceedings.

Process:

Start times, conduct, audibility, victim/public safety, etc.

Substance:

Plea bargains, dispositions, departure from sentencing

guidelines, victim and defendant statements, victim

safety, pre-investigation, etc.

You are monitoring the ENTIRE process, including what happens before, during and after appearances, both in the gallery and in the attorney area. You may overhear interesting comments or feedback in the elevators or other areas adjacent to the courts.
